---

<ComparisonLayout
  title="Kajabi vs Teachable (2026): All-in-One Business Builder vs Focused Course Platform"
  description="Kajabi and Teachable serve course creators with different philosophies. This comparison breaks down which platform fits experts, academies, and companies selling online courses."
  platform1="Kajabi"
  platform2="Teachable"
  breadcrumbs={[{ label: 'Comparisons', href: '/compare' }, { label: 'Kajabi vs Teachable' }]}
  lastUpdated="2026-03-22"
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>

  <h1>Kajabi vs Teachable: All-in-One Business Builder vs Focused Course Platform</h1>

  <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 mt-4 mb-8">
    Kajabi and Teachable are two of the most popular platforms for selling online courses, but they serve different business models. Kajabi is an all-in-one business platform with built-in email marketing, sales funnels, and landing pages designed for experts who want to consolidate their tech stack. Teachable is a focused course platform with lower entry pricing, stronger course delivery features, and native mobile apps on all plans. The right choice depends on whether you prioritize marketing automation and business consolidation (Kajabi) or course quality and value (Teachable).
  </p>

  <section class="my-8">
    <h2>Who This Comparison Is For</h2>
    <p>
      This comparison is for experts, coaches, consultants, and academies evaluating platforms to sell online courses, coaching programs, or digital products. If you're deciding between an all-in-one business platform and a focused course platform — or trying to understand whether Kajabi's marketing tools justify its premium pricing — this breakdown will help you make the right call.
    </p>
  </section>

  <KeyTakeaways items={[
    "Kajabi is an all-in-one business platform; Teachable is a focused course platform with different strengths.",
    "Kajabi wins on marketing automation, sales funnels, and business consolidation — it replaces 3–5 separate tools.",
    "Teachable wins on pricing, mobile app accessibility, course delivery features, and API accessibility.",
    "Teachable is significantly cheaper at every tier, but Kajabi may save money if you'd otherwise pay for separate marketing tools.",
    "Both platforms serve customer education, but Kajabi treats it as a growth engine while Teachable focuses on delivery quality.",
    "Teachable includes native mobile apps on all plans; Kajabi's branded app requires the $399/mo Pro plan."
  ]} />

  <section class="my-10">
    <h2>Why This Comparison Matters</h2>
    <p>
      Kajabi and Teachable frequently appear on the same shortlists despite serving fundamentally different approaches to the online course business. Both let you create and sell courses. Both support coaching and communities. Both have invested in AI features. But they solve different problems.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3">
      Kajabi starts from business infrastructure. Its architecture is designed around consolidating your entire tech stack — email marketing, sales funnels, landing pages, courses, communities, and coaching — into a single integrated platform. The value proposition is simplicity and the elimination of separate subscriptions.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3">
      Teachable starts from course delivery. Its architecture is optimized for creating high-quality learning experiences with strong mobile support, compliance tracking, and AI-powered content tools. The value proposition is focused course delivery at accessible pricing, accepting that you may need external tools for advanced marketing.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3">
      Neither platform is objectively better. They serve different business models. The risk is choosing based on feature checklists rather than business model fit: paying Kajabi's premium when you don't need its marketing tools, or choosing Teachable and discovering you need to pay for marketing software anyway.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="my-10">
    <h2>Quick Comparison</h2>
    <ComparisonTable
      headers={["Kajabi", "Teachable"]}
      rows={comparisonRows}
      highlight={0}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="my-10">
    <h2>Where Kajabi Wins</h2>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Marketing Automation and Sales Funnels</h3>
    <p>
      Kajabi's marketing capabilities are genuinely sophisticated and rival standalone platforms like ConvertKit or ActiveCampaign. Built-in email sequences, behavioral triggers, pre-built funnel blueprints, and advanced automation allow you to create sophisticated customer journeys without Zapier. When a student watches 50% of a video, that can trigger an abandonment email automatically — no external tools required.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">All-in-One Business Consolidation</h3>
    <p>
      Kajabi replaces your website builder, email marketing platform, funnel builder, landing page tool, and course platform. For businesses currently paying for ConvertKit ($29–$79/mo), ClickFunnels ($97–$297/mo), and a course platform separately, Kajabi's $199/mo Growth plan can actually reduce total software costs while simplifying operations.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Professional Website and Branding</h3>
    <p>
      Kajabi includes a full website builder with professional templates, blog functionality, and polished design out of the box. You can run your entire web presence from Kajabi without needing WordPress, Squarespace, or another site builder. The design quality is consistently high across templates.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Native Coaching Management</h3>
    <p>
      Kajabi offers native 1:1 and group coaching management with intake forms, session scheduling, client notes, and package-based coaching programs. This is a unique strength — few competitors offer this level of integrated coaching support without third-party tools.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Integrated Analytics</h3>
    <p>
      Because Kajabi owns the entire funnel from lead capture to purchase, it can show you exactly which email sequences and landing pages drive enrollments. This end-to-end visibility is harder to achieve when stitching together separate tools.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="my-10">
    <h2>Where Teachable Wins</h2>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Pricing and Value</h3>
    <p>
      Teachable is significantly cheaper at every tier. The Starter plan at $29/mo (annual) is less than a quarter of Kajabi's $143/mo entry point. Even at comparable capability levels — Teachable's Builder plan at $69/mo vs Kajabi's Basic at $143/mo — Teachable costs less than half. For businesses that already have marketing tools or don't need advanced funnels, this price difference is substantial.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Mobile App Accessibility</h3>
    <p>
      Teachable includes native iOS and Android apps on all plans, including the $29/mo Starter tier. Students get offline viewing, push notifications, and a polished mobile experience. Kajabi offers a free student app on all plans, but a branded app with your own branding requires the Pro plan at $399/mo. For mobile-first businesses, Teachable's inclusive approach is a significant advantage.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Course Delivery and Student Experience</h3>
    <p>
      Teachable's course builder is more refined than Kajabi's, with features like auto-graded quizzes, short-answer assessments, course compliance tracking, certificates on all plans, and AI-powered subtitle generation with translation into 70+ languages. The student experience is cleaner and more learning-focused.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Global Tax Handling</h3>
    <p>
      Teachable automatically handles US sales tax, EU VAT, and GST collection and remittance on all plans. This eliminates a significant administrative burden for global sellers. Kajabi has more limited tax automation and may require third-party integrations for full compliance.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">API and Integration Accessibility</h3>
    <p>
      Teachable offers API access starting at the Growth plan ($139/mo annual) with 10,000 requests/month. Kajabi locks API access behind the Pro plan at $399/mo. For businesses that need custom integrations or want to connect their course platform to existing tools, Teachable's lower barrier to API access is meaningful.
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-6">Affiliate Program on All Plans</h3>
    <p>
      Teachable includes affiliate program functionality on all paid plans, including the $29/mo Starter. Kajabi restricts affiliates to the Growth plan ($199/mo) and above. For creators who want to leverage partners and students to drive enrollments from day one, this is a significant difference.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="my-10">
    <h2>The Decision Framework</h2>
    <p class="mb-6">
      Rather than comparing features line by line, use these three buyer forks to clarify which platform model fits your situation.
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold mb-2">Fork 1: All-in-One vs Modular Stack</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
          If you want a single platform to run your entire business — website, email, funnels, courses, and community — and you would otherwise pay for 3–5 separate tools, <strong>choose Kajabi</strong>. The consolidation saves money and complexity. If you already have marketing tools you like, or prefer to choose best-in-class tools for each function, <strong>choose Teachable</strong> and build your own stack.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold mb-2">Fork 2: Marketing vs Delivery Priority</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
          If your business growth depends heavily on email sequences, sales funnels, and landing page optimization — and you want these integrated with your course platform — <strong>choose Kajabi</strong>. If you prioritize the learning experience, mobile accessibility, and course quality over marketing automation — <strong>choose Teachable</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold mb-2">Fork 3: Budget and Stage</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-600 mb-3">
          If you're just starting out, testing offers, or operating on a tight budget, <strong>choose Teachable's Builder plan</strong> ($69/mo annual) for the best combination of features and value. If you're an established business doing $10,000+/mo and want to consolidate your tech stack, <strong>evaluate Kajabi's Growth plan</strong> ($199/mo annual) against your current tool costs — it may actually save money.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="my-10">
    <h2>Who Should Choose Which</h2>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mt-6">
      <div class="border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold mb-3">Choose Kajabi if you:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600">
          <li>Want one platform for your entire business (website, email, funnels, courses)</li>
          <li>Currently pay for multiple marketing tools and want to consolidate</li>
          <li>Depend on email sequences and sales funnels for revenue growth</li>
          <li>Offer coaching programs alongside courses</li>
          <li>Value integrated analytics across the entire customer journey</li>
          <li>Are an established expert with existing revenue to justify the premium</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-slate-200 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="text-navy font-semibold mb-3">Choose Teachable if you:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-slate-600">
          <li>Want the best value and lowest total cost of ownership</li>
          <li>Already have marketing tools you like (ConvertKit, Mailchimp, etc.)</li>
          <li>Need mobile apps for students without paying $399/mo</li>
          <li>Prioritize course delivery quality and student experience</li>
          <li>Sell globally and need automatic tax handling</li>
          <li>Want API access without paying for the highest tier</li>
          <li>Are starting out and need accessible entry pricing</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <LeadFormModal
    ctaTitle="Not sure which platform fits your business model?"
    ctaDescription="Share your use case and we'll help you determine whether an all-in-one platform or focused course platform makes more sense for your situation."
    ctaButtonText="Get My Recommendation"
  />

  <FAQ items={faqItems} />

  <RelatedPages pages={relatedPages} />

</ComparisonLayout>
